To further determine the physicochemical properties of bio-nanocomposite film, the thickness, mechanical, and water vapor permeability (WVP) properties of films can be observed in Table 1 . No noticeable difference in thickness was found between neat and CDs-doped nanocomposite pectin film because CDs were filled within the interstices of the pectin molecules. The strength and stiffness parameters were further used to determine the mechanical properties of films. The addition of CDs significantly improved the tensile strength and elongation at break (EAB) of the original pectin film. Previous studies have reported that the interaction between the pectin matrix and CDs can significantly enhance the tensile strength and improve the elongation properties (Kiadeh et al., 2022). The favorable interfacial interactions between the pectin matrix and CDs are considered as key factors in improving the physical properties (Kiadeh et al., 2022). Besides, the WVP and water solubility of neat film were similar with CDs-doped bio-nanocomposite film, indicating that the addition of CDs would not affect the hydrophilicity of pectin film. In addition, the transparency property of film was evaluated by determined the light transmittance at 400–1000 nm. As shown in Fig. 5 , the transmittance of pectin film was increased with the increase of wavelength. Apparently, the transmittance of bio-nanocomposite film was reduced by the addition of CDs, indicating the reduction of transparency of CDs/pectin film (
Table S1
).
